SIMPLE: laager
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: laager
<hw>laa"ger</hw> <pr>(l⟦add⟧"g⟦etil⟧r <it>or</it> l⟦aum⟧"g⟦etil⟧r)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D., also <ets>leger</ets>. Cf. 2d <er>Leaguer</er>,
<er>Lair</er>.]</ety> <def>A camp, especially one surrounded by a
circular formation of travelers' wagons for temporary defense.</def>
<mark>[South Africa]</mark>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> lager.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wagons . . . can be readily formed into a <qex>laager</qex>, a
camp, by being drawn into a circle, with the oxen placed inside and so
kept safe from the attacks of wild beasts.</q> <rj><qau>James
Bryce.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Laager</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Laager
<hw>Laa"ger</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Laager</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To form into, or camp in, a laager, or
protected camp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Laas</ent>⟦br⟧
